## Risk 4: Governance Fatigue

**The risk**: On-chain governance participants resist ongoing program oversight requirements because every operational decision requires full community engagement. Participation declines, renewal processes become rubber stamps, and programs persist through inertia.

**Why it happens**: Governance participation requires time and attention. Operational programs generate many small decisions. If every decision requires community voting, governance participants will disengage — producing low-quality oversight rather than no oversight.

**Warning signals**:
- Renewal proposals pass without substantive discussion
- Governance vote participation has declined since program launch
- Operators informally ask governance participants what decisions they want to see rather than reporting what decisions were made
- Participants describe program oversight as "a formality"

### Mitigation Protocol

**Default-approve for compliant programs**: Programs that meet all KPI thresholds for two consecutive quarters receive an automatic renewal recommendation. Governance confirms with a simple ratification (not a full re-evaluation). This dramatically reduces the number of active decisions governance must process.

**Escalation-only model**: Routine operational decisions (individual retainer evaluations within published criteria, bounty approvals within budget, pathway cohort management) are handled by the operator without governance vote. Governance acts only on: budget overruns, scope expansion requests, operator performance concerns, metric-triggered escalations, and charter renewals.

**Off-chain oversight structure**: Operational detail is managed by dedicated committees (technical review, program oversight) that operate off-chain and report to governance on a defined cadence. This separation reduces governance overhead without reducing accountability.

**Meaningful renewal**: Charter renewals must require scope redefinition — identical renewals are not permitted. This ensures that governance engagement during renewal is substantive, not performative.

**Quarterly summary model**: Governance receives consolidated quarterly reports rather than per-decision approval requests. The report flags any items requiring governance action. Everything else is for information only.

